04952nam a22007455i 9780674419407DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)900717695  a97806744194077 a10.4159/harvard.97806744194072doi  a(DE-B1597)427258  a(OCoLC)880147810  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHB863 7aBIO0060002bisacsh1 aMayhew, Robert J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMalthus :bThe Life and Legacies of an Untimely Prophet /cRobert J. Mayhew. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tPrologue: Opening the Door on Malthus’s Roller Coaster -- t1. Before Malthus -- t2. Prophets of Perfection: A Revolutionary Triptych -- t3. Malthus’s Essay and the Quiet Revolution of 1798 -- t4. Malthus as the Malign Muse of Romanticism -- t5. Malthus and the Making of Environmental Economics -- t6. Malthus and the Victorians -- t7. Malthus and the Dismal Age -- t8. Malthus the Transatlantic Celebrity -- t9. Malthus Today -- tEpilogue: High Time for the Untimely Prophet -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThomas Robert Malthus's An Essay on the Principle of Population was an immediate succès de scandale when it appeared in 1798. Arguing that nature is niggardly and that societies, both human and animal, tend to overstep the limits of natural resources in "perpetual oscillation between happiness and misery," he found himself attacked on all sides--by Romantic poets, utopian thinkers, and the religious establishment. Though Malthus has never disappeared, he has been perpetually misunderstood. This book is at once a major reassessment of Malthus's ideas and an intellectual history of the origins of modern debates about demography, resources, and the environment. Against the ferment of Enlightenment ideals about the perfectibility of mankind and the grim realities of life in the eighteenth century, Robert Mayhew explains the genesis of the Essay and Malthus's preoccupation with birth and death rates. He traces Malthus's collision course with the Lake poets, his important revisions to the Essay, and composition of his other great work, Principles of Political Economy. Mayhew suggests we see the author in his later writings as an environmental economist for his persistent concern with natural resources, land, and the conditions of their use. Mayhew then pursues Malthus's many afterlives in the Victorian world and beyond. Today, the Malthusian dilemma makes itself felt once again, as demography and climate change come together on the same environmental agenda. By opening a new door onto Malthus's arguments and their transmission to the present day, Robert Mayhew gives historical depth to our current planetary concerns.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDemografie. 0aDemographers. 0aEconomen. 0aEconomists. 0aSozialwissenschaften, Soziologie, Anthropologie. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2014z9783110370225oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067441940740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674419407423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674419407.jpg  a978-3-11-066590-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EB